		<title>The most popular stories of 2016</title>
		<link>http://arstechnica.com/staff/2016/12/the-most-popular-stories-of-2016/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 24 Dec 2016 13:00:24 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Eric Bangeman]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Staff]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://arstechnica.com/?p=1012947</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Our top 10 features and top 10 news stories by pageviews.]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="rss-wrap">
<figure class="intro-image intro-left"><img src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/ars-top-posts-800x450.jpg"><p class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/ars-top-posts.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="450" data-width="800">Enlarge</a> (credit: Aurich Lawson)</p>  </figure><div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>What a year 2016 was. There was a US presidential election with an unexpected result, a UK referendum on leaving the European Union with an unexpected result, a constitutional referendum in Italy with an unexpected result... you get the picture. One thing that <em>wasn't</em> out of the ordinary was a year of outstanding stories from the writers at Ars Technica.</p>
<p>2016 saw record traffic for Ars, both in pages served and unique visitors. People not only want to read our takes on the shiniest, newest gadgets; they stop by Ars to learn not only what's going on but why it's important.</p>
<p>As we prepare to put 2016 in our collective rearview mirror, we thought you'd like a look at our top 10 multipage features and single-page news stories from 2016.</p>
